{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608964"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.76,0.05,0.14,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8747"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59365"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10627"},{"type":"tags","id":"10628"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELabour is divided into three stages.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the beginning of the second stage of labour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delivery of the baby","Full cervical dilatation (10 cm)","Initial cervical effacement","Regular uterine contractions","Rupture of membranes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe second stage of labour begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Efull cervical dilatation (10 cm)\u003C/strong\u003E and ends with \u003Cstrong\u003Edelivery of the baby\u003C/strong\u003E. This stage is characterised by active maternal pushing and descent of the foetus through the birth canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other important events in labour:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial cervical effacement\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the latent phase of the first stage of labour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular uterine contractions\u003C/strong\u003E typically mark the onset of active labour in the first stage\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of membranes\u003C/strong\u003E can occur at any point before or during the first stage of labour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first stage of labour involves cervical effacement and dilatation. The third stage begins after delivery of the baby and ends with delivery of the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The second stage of labour begins at full cervical dilatation (10 cm) and ends with delivery of the baby.","Labour has three distinct stages: first (cervical dilatation), second (foetal delivery), and third (placental delivery)."],"references":["Labor S, Maguire S. The Pain of Labour. Rev Pain. 2008 Dec;2(2):15-9. doi: 10.1177/204946370800200205. PMID: 26526404; PMCID: PMC4589939.","Lemos A, Amorim MM, Dornelas de Andrade A, de Souza AI, Cabral Filho JE, Correia JB. Pushing/bearing down methods for the second stage of labour. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017 Mar 26;3(3):CD009124. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD009124.pub3. PMID: 28349526; PMCID: PMC6464699.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59365"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59365"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T07:36:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T07:37:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8747"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73889"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T2